The work done on the gas for each step of a single cycle is calculated using $W = -integral P d V$:
  - Step 1: $W_12 = -P_1(V_2 - V_1)$
  - Step 2: $W_23 = 0$
  - Step 3: $W_34 = -P_2(V_1 - V_2) = P_2(V_2 - V_1)$
  - Step 4: $W_41 = 0$
  
  Net work per cycle: $W_"net" = (P_2 - P_1)(V_2 - V_1)$
  
  For 100 cycles ($N = 100$) with converted SI units ($1 " atm" = 1.013 times 10^5 " Pa"$, $1 " L" = 1.0 times 10^(-3) " m"^3$):
  $ W_"tot" = 100 times (1.0 - 3.0) times (1.013 times 10^5 " Pa") times (2.0 - 1.0) times 10^(-3) " m"^3 \
  W_"tot" = 100 times (-2.026 times 10^5) times 1.0 times 10^(-3) = -20.26 " kJ" approx -20.3 " kJ" $